        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/eeec80237213c91e5bab56b77ac5b8ca?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 16878,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 37213,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/37213/duffymo",
                "reputation": 309604,
                "display_name": "duffymo",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1295313773,
            "creation_date": 1295313773,
            "body": "<p>Any number of equations?  The means of solution is different depending on how that compares to the number of unknowns.<\/p>\n\n<p>If N(unknowns) &lt; N(equations), you'll need to do a least squares solution to obtain the coefficients.<\/p>\n\n<p>If N(unknowns) = N(equations), you can solve using LU decomposition with pivoting or singular value decomposition.<\/p>\n\n<p>If N(unknowns) > N(equations), you'll need to do a singular value decomposition, which will give you the null space and the best solution it can.<\/p>\n\n<p>If the number of equations is <em>very<\/em> large, you may need to think about exploiting sparseness or writing the matrix out to disk and solving it in steps.<\/p>\n\n<p>The Apache Commons Math library contains all these.  I recommend it if you're coding in Java.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 4719659,
            "question_id": 4717655
        }
